{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01WhQoNCZsMpnYEZNuZdcuRx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the customer feedback processing service to determine the minimum test infrastructure level.\n\n**Context:**\n- Service receives text reviews\n- Two outputs: sentiment score (keyword-frequency analyzer) + explanation (separate analyzer)\n- Keyword analyzer: configurable thresholds\n- Explanation analyzer: natural language reasoning about sentiment drivers\n\nLet me reason through each behavior:\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 1: Keyword-frequency analyzer assigns correct sentiment with only configured words\n\n\"The keyword-frequency analyzer assigns the correct sentiment when the review contains only words from the configured positive and negative word lists.\"\n\n**Analysis:**\n- This is purely deterministic algorithm logic\n- Input: text string + configuration (word lists + thresholds)\n- Output: sentiment score\n- No external dependencies (no network, no LLM, no filesystem needed to pass)\n- No OS-level behavior involved\n- No real infrastructure needed\n\n**MOCK-MISS?** No. A pure unit test with mocked config and test text would catch if the logic is wrong.\n\n**REAL-INFRA?** No. The analyzer doesn't depend on external I/O.\n\n**LLM-DEP?** No. This is deterministic keyword matching.\n\n**Minimum Level:** Unit\n- One local function boundary: the keyword analyzer logic\n- Input: text + config dict\n- Output: sentiment score\n- Test description: Pass a review like \"great amazing wonderful\" with positive word list [\"great\", \"amazing\", \"wonderful\"], verify it returns POSITIVE\n\n**Test Description:** \"Verify keyword analyzer returns POSITIVE when review contains only words from positive word list with proper thresholds\"\n\n**Level Probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.95 (very likely this is sufficient)\n- Integration: 0.04 (only if you need to test config file loading, which isn't part of the core behavior)\n- System: 0.01 (no real reason to go here)\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n\n## Behavior 2: Explanation analyzer produces reasoning that references specific phrases from the original review, not generic boilerplate\n\n\"The explanation analyzer produces reasoning that references specific phrases from the original review, not generic boilerplate.\"\n\n**Analysis:**\n- The explanation analyzer generates natural language reasoning about sentiment drivers\n- Core requirement: must cite actual phrases from the input review, not return templated responses\n- This tests whether the analyzer actually processes the review content or just outputs canned text\n\n**MOCK-MISS?** Yes. A mock would return a fixed string regardless of input, so it wouldn't catch if the real implementation produces generic boilerplate instead of review-specific reasoning.\n\n**REAL-INFRA?** Depends on implementation. If the analyzer uses an LLM, you need real infrastructure. If it's rule-based phrase extraction, you might not.\n\n**LLM-DEP?** Likely. Natural language reasoning typically requires an LLM or similar model.\n\n**Minimum Level:** Integration or System\n- If LLM-based: System level (need real LLM calls to verify it produces specific reasoning)\n- If rule-based: Integration level (test the analyzer with real review text to verify phrase extraction works)\n- The behavior requires exercising the actual analyzer logic with real input to catch generic output failures\n\n**Test Description:** \"Verify explanation analyzer references specific phrases from review instead of returning generic templates\"\n\n**Level Probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.05 (mocks would hide the actual behavior)\n- Integration: 0.40 (if rule-based phrase extraction)\n- System: 0.50 (if LLM-dependent)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (if multi-step reasoning needed)\n- Workflow: 0.0 The core question is whether the analyzer relies on an LLM or uses deterministic logic. If it calls an LLM